text:
come follow us this week (18th-24th november) on twitter as we curate safe city's handle @pinthecreep.

we aim to expand the conversation around the need to see men and boys as allies and not perpetrators while addressing #genderbasedviolence and discrimination. we will also be hosting a #tweetchat on the 23rd of november and would love to hear your views on this.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
the silence of the girls~ pat barker
*
"i do what no man before me has ever done, i kiss the hands of the man who killed my son,â€ says priam when he begs for hectorâ€™s body.
*
but in our moment of pity for the great priam who is begging his sons murderer for his defiled body, he never for a moment turns that same glance at briseis and the other slaves in the camp who are now raped by the men who take have murdered their own families and taken them from the status of women to objects. priam is resigned to his daughters fates he refuses to try and take briseis back with him, she is not worth the trouble.
*
pat barker is a good writer, and conveys a sense of timelessness in her story â€“the timelessness experienced by a slave for whom nothing changes until she is passed on to a new owner. aside from this, rendering of a human to an object wasnâ€™t well done, and the repetitions seemed more forced than natural. barker could have been more subtle about this. briseis is confused about feeling pity for patroclus, and not completely hating achilles (her stockholm syndrome), but her anger at the death of her family and her new lot in life doesnâ€™t come to surface in the slightest. while the book has some really interesting moments (such as the execution of polyxena and her hair being cut), the rest was a superficial blur.
*
i appreciated the fact that the gods were seen to be real entities, and that the plight of women was nothing of significance to them â€“a hopeless note that women did not matter even to them. but even so, barker could have been more considerate of the language she used; i get that achilles is a man-child, but him shouting â€œmummy, mummyâ€ into the water seems a bit out of place.
*
as someone who loved circe by madeline miller and was really looking forward to this retelling, i was left disappointed.
*

tweet_full: #scam #ac #army #man #money #beauty #smiles #metoo #christian #faithquotes

text:
i. you say,
you can't wait to be 20,
and find peace,
 in beer bottles like your dad does.

ii. you say,
you found love last night.

iii. you were 14,
when you first found love.

and you didn't know back then, 
love is like paris in 1789,
nobody leaves not angry, 
nobody leaves not a rebel.

love is like russia, 
in revolution.

hand grenades in your pocket, 
timebomb in your back pack.

you're here only to break a few homes.

steal rum off of your daddy's bar,
burn cigarettes in the back of your car.

you're so young and angry, 
you need to be hollow,
to set free.

so all you do is go on war.

keep your love 
like sodium in your hand,
burn your beloved 
everytime he gasps for air.

your throat will burn,
as if you swallowed,
a bottle of hcl,

everytime you say i love you.

and so you'll swallow lies,
like ice cream sunades,
from your childhood,
that you had,
in your favourite alley.

when your wrists were skin,
and all you did,
was collect popsicle sticks.
(now all you do is collect broken 
architecture and hang it around your neck)

iv. you were 16,
when you first fell out of love.

there are curses
and love potions on your floor.

home is not like how he left it,

with daisies and chocolate cakes,

it's full of 
hair that you cut 
and forgot to drain (he was on your mind)

poems you didn't write
(you didn't want him out of your mind)

v. you've been in and out 
of love,

you've tatsed the blood 
on both sides.

yet you're going in again,

you feel this is different,

you're 17.

vi. you're 20 
you came home last night 
your masacra was a mess,

you've emptied 
five beer bottles tonight,
you've still not fallen out of it.
.
.
utopaingrey.
(@utopiangrey)
.
.
.

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
this image is from an interactive catalouge i made of every recorded sexual assault in san francisco last year, the most recent complete record. the rudimentary website accesses official police records. each marker notes whether or not an arrest was made in the case and updates the information live. you can filter through the startling number of sexual assault classifications by police district on a sattelite map. zoom in, investigate and see how rarely these crimes are solved. link in bio.

text:
protests have taken place in ireland after the underwear a teenager was wearing was cited in the trial of a man accused of raping her. in the course of the trial, the defense lawyer held up a pair of the 17-year-oldâ€™s underwear in court, and asked: â€œyou have to look at the way she was dressed. she was wearing a thong with a lace front.â€ a 27-year-old man was found not guilty of raping the teenager earlier this month. the lawyerâ€™s comments provoked immediate criticism, and women gathered at demonstrations across ireland to protest the handling of the court case on wednesday. their anger built on an online movement around #thisisnotconsent after the trial, kickstarted by the campaign group i believe her. â€œsimply put, clothing is not consent. this kind of victim blaming is archaic and had no place in our court system,â€ susan dillon, who was among a group of women who started the hashtag, told buzzfeed news (ğŸ“·: getty, lilthumper408, samana1988, maireos, catalanaalor via twitter)
-

text:
the past week has easily been the most rewarding, memorable ama meeting that iâ€™ve been a part of and there are a lot of people to thank for that. i had the honor of serving on the ama resident and fellow section governing council, leading the hod delegation with my partner-in-crime, delegate @markykash and the rest of our governing council consisting of chair colin murphy, immediate past chair @mlecuyer28, vice chair gunjan malhotra, board of trustees representative @ryanribeira, speaker eli freiman, vice speaker laura halpin, and member-at-large @hunterpattison. we were also able to welcome our chair-elect, the incomparable tani malhotra, our next candidate for the board of trustees @graysonwilkes.

in the house of delegates, we proudly supported policies to study patterns of physician suicide, identify models for systems addressing opioid mitigation, take a stronger stance on public health concerns related to vaping and e-cigarettes (just a day before the fda took a harder stance on the issue!), improve screening for domestic violence in lgbtq patients, recognize the full spectrum of gender identity and fluidity in response to recent moves by the trump administration, support the daca and dalca populations, increase support for post-marketing surveillance studies for drugs approved by fda-expedited review pathways, update and improve on principles and recommendations for addressing and mitigating student debt, continue to oppose unfunded mandates and their negative impact on patients and physicians, and improve ethical guidance on healthcare decision-making for parents and their children, to name just a few!

we also heard powerful testimony and were forced to take a hard look at internal policies on sexual and non-sexual harassment and recommended unanimously to bring in outside counsel to improve the processes and protect attendees and set an example on self-policing and combating harassment.

we also continued an ongoing discussion of gun violence as a major public health crisis, both as individuals (#thisisourlane) and as an organization. iâ€™m excited to see whatâ€™s next and energized!
#amamtg #amarfs #membersmovemedicine @amermedicalassn #metoo #timesup

in the house of delegates, we proudly suppoed policies to study patterns of physician suicide, identify models for systems addressing opioid mitigation, take a stronger stance on public health concerns related to vaping and e-cigarettes (just a day before the fda took a harder stance on the issue!), improve screening for domestic violence in lgbtq patients, recognize the full spectrum of gender identity and fluidity in response to recent moves by the trump administration, suppo the daca and dalca populations, increase suppo for post-marketing surveillance studies for drugs approved by fda-expedited review pathways, update and improve on principles and recommendations for addressing and mitigating student debt, continue to oppose unfunded mandates and their negative impact on patients and physicians, and improve ethical guidance on healthcare decision-making for parents and their children, to name just a few!

we also heard powerful testimony and were forced to take a hard look at internal policies on sexual and non-sexual harassment and recommended uimously to bring in outside counsel to improve the processes and protect attendees and set an example on self-policing and combating harassment.

we also continued an ongoing discussion of gun violence as a major public health crisis, both as individuals ( and as an organization. iâ€™m excited to see whatâ€™s next and energized!

text:
pre-holiday tip 1...
yesterday we discussed starting a dialogue with your child in preparation for all of the family time they may be experiencing over the next month. our first tip is to ask your child open-ended questions about the people who they may be encountering during these family events. for example, "how do you feel about going to see grandpa next week?", "what do you like about uncle jim and what don't you like about him?", or "what do you think about pastor smith or cousin sara?". give them the opportunity to answer the questions completely before asking additional clarifying questions and don't trivialize their opinions or try to convince them that they shouldn't feel the way they do. remember, how you as a parent experience a friend or family member can be very different than how a child experiences that individual, especially when sexual abuse is occurring/has occurred. it is critical that you listen attentively in these moments and gently probe when you hear responses that cause you concern or their body language, facial expressions or tone changes when a specific individual is being discussed. if you aren't sure if there is a need for concern based on your child's explanation about a specific family member or friend, take measures to keep your child isolated from this individual until you are sure.  #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

text:
read caption-
does it ever feel like all this is just too much to handle?
like you sitting in your home, with your family. 
your dad is sipping his evening tea while your mother is watching her favourite show and they are even conversing in between. 
everything is fine. 
it's okay.
because that is what "fine" is supposed to be like, right?
and suddenly, you are not able to breathe. 
it's as if this "fine" environment is suffocating you.
you think that maybe it's because of the noise and you'll feel better if you just go outside and walk in the balcony. 
but even when you are walking, you are still not able to breathe. and you start thinking that maybe it's the silence. 
it's like the air is going in through your mouth but it's not reaching to your lungs, your body or most importantly, to your soul. you think that you're going to die, this is the end. suddenly somebody taps on your shoulder, you look back, it's your parents with concerned look on their faces. and in that exact moment, the air from this entire universe gathers and satisfies your soul. 
but, as the moment passes by you, are you thankful? 
do you think that, thank god that you have some people in your life who'll never leave you, no matter what happens? 
do you feel thankful towards the universe for giving you this one more precious chance to breathe peacefully? 
or do you go on, cursing this blissful life that you are given? 
claiming that how your life sucks while there are thousands of people out there who'll maybe even die, just to live a day of this blessed life of yours? 
what is it?

text:
secretary devos just proposed a rule that would make schools less safe for survivors of sexual assault and harassment, when there is already alarmingly high rates of campus sexual assaults and harassment that go unreported.

it promotes a process that inappropriately favors the accused and would let schools ignore their responsibility under title ix to respond promptly and fairly to complaints of sexual violence.

we will continue to support survivors.

text:
"i wouldn't have been able to verbalise what had happened to me because anyway i didn't know what had happened to me." you did this to yourself, 2011.

many of the images from my piece are accompanied by text. i collected these pieces of text from courtroom transcripts, news reports and interviews in liz kelly's 'surviving sexual violence' (1988). back in 2011 these seemed the best sources of speech about sexual violence. nowadays i suppose i could use the huge mass of descriptive statements on hashtags like #metoo. there is much more out there than in 2011, but somehow not much has changed. there is an amnesia about sexual violence - survivor stories have been transcribed again and again each decade, but somehow we still think these stories are new. we still think their revelation will issue change. the more i research this topic, the more i think that survivor stories are not the avenue to lasting legal and political change that will protect survivors and would-be survivors. 
#sexualviolence #survivors #wordsandpictures

text: #gratitude day 4. today because i feel more miserable with a cold on top of incredible stress of this week. iâ€™m going to say something i almost never say. i am grateful i am still here. iâ€™ve gone back and forth about sharing this on social media because thereâ€™s many backstabbers who use posts against people. but in light of the #metoo movement iâ€™ve decided to share. iâ€™ve struggled with major depression most of my life. iâ€™ve been suicidal many, many times but yet i continue to be here, mostly because i donâ€™t want to rush into something thatâ€™s coming for all of us any way. i also have chronic pain conditions. i know i have many fellow #spoonies who understand. every day when i get out of bed (iâ€™d love to say wake up but i rarely sleep) i want to give up. i want to die because of the horrible pain that i am in. but instead i get up, go to work and try to lead as normal a life as i can. iâ€™ve tried many things, therapy, medications, multiple medications, exercise, trying to eat better, attempting a social life, herbal supplements, meditation, etc. you name it, iâ€™ve probably tried.i try not to complain too much because people do not care. people are selfish and only care about themselves, weâ€™re in a â€œme first and onlyâ€ type of culture. but this is all because i want to share a specific part of what has helped me. if you are suicidal, odds are you donâ€™t want to die, but some part of your life does need to die. if you are low look at your life, what in it needs to die? what do you need to stop giving energy to? family? friends? need a new job? try to identify it if you possibly can (which i know is a monumental task Â when you have depression) and do it. stop giving it energy, cut it out, get rid of it, kill it, change it. give yourself back that energy to use in literally anything that brings you even the slightest glimmer of hope. and if you think that no one in the world cares, i assure you that someone, somewhere in some aspect cares about you. even if itâ€™s the person you held the door open for at dunkin and gave you a genuine smile. i care about you. i get it. and i see you, and i love you. thank you for staying in this world with me. i am grateful for you too.

text:
hari ini 16 november adalah hari toleransi sedunia. saya & teman teman meluncurkan festival film ber nama 16filmfest yang mendukung toleransi atas segala perbedaan di muka bumi ini. perbedaan etnis, budaya, agama, semua seharusnya bisa memperkaya hidup kita dan memperkuat persaudaraan sesama.
namun, perbedaan kadang melegitimasi terjadinya kekerasan. padahal manusia bernurani dan kemanusiaan seharusnya tidak mentolerir segala bentuk kekerasan. bahasa kerennya zero tolerance, bahasa indonesianya nol toleransi. lewat pemutaran film, @enam belasffest mengkampanyekan nol toleransi atas kekerasan berbasis gender dan seksual.
festival film yang akan ber langsung selama 16 hari ini, dari mulai 25 november sampai 10 desember, akan memutar 16 film panjang dan 16 film pendek yang pastinya bisa meningkatkan awareness kita atas segala bentuk kekerasan sambil mencari solusi bersama untuk mengakhirinya. terimakasih @komnas_perempuan @unaids.id @aliansi1visi @viu indonesia@nadianasoetion & semua teman2 filmmakers yang sudah berpartisipadi meminjamkan filmnya, juga semua volunteers & ambassadors tersayang  #toleranceday #internationaltoleranceday #16daysofactivism #16haktp #zerotolerance #genderbasedviolence #hearmetoo #metoo #movement #indonesia #filmfestival #communityfirst #empoweringwomen #allequal #lgbtiq #rainbowwarriors #enambelasffest
name: Nia Dinata

text:
a story that i've been horrified reading about this week is that of the court case of the alleged rapist of a 17 year old girl in #ireland the 27 year old man's defence lawyer basically said that how this girl was dressed was a problem and that she was effectively up for it. what she was referring to was the #lace front #thong that the victim was wearing. the fact that this sentiment came from a woman has absolutely blown my mind ğŸ˜¬
.
.
the man was found not guilty. now whether he is or not, i don't know, but what i do know is that the underwear any woman chooses to wear on any given day does not relate to her willingness to have sex with someone. it got me to thinking that nearly all of my female clients wear thongs when they see me, and many of my male clients go completely naked purely as it makes it easier for me to work the glutes without material getting in the way. this lawyer would presumably think that the sexual abuse of any of these people would be justified as they chose to get naked or wear a thong ğŸ¤” yeah seriously, how frightening?! .
.
now my lawyer husband made the point that as the defence lawyer, she'll say anything to try and get her client off as that's her job. i get that, but surely at some point in cases like this, this level of opinion cannot be applied. i'm amazed the judge didn't ask for the statement to be retracted. i'm sure this woman doesn't believe this girl deserved it, but what are we teaching young men and boys when that is put forward as a reasonable excuse to rape someone. the mind boggles!
.
so women in support of this young lady are posting pics of their thongs with the hashtag #thisisnotconsent so here is one of mine, just casually left in my hallway! it's simple folks.... #nomeansno #ibelieveher
.

new session alert! whether you're on a diet, no diet or hate diets, diet culture impacts us all. and it's costing us a pretty penny financially, mentally and emotionally. which is why i'm thrilled to have @mburton0214 teach this workshop at lola la.
---- how the diet and wellness industry is making you broke on every level

the health and wellness industry has been pioneered and dominated by women. women are also primarily responsible for making the health and wellness industry a multi trillion dollar industry. our current culture dictates that not only should women be and do it all, they should look (and feel!) flawlessly amazing while accomplishing their goals and living their best lives (insert eye roll here). even in the empowered #metoo era, women are still being convinced that they need to invest their money and energy in the dreams promised by the diet and wellness industry in order to even deserve a healthy, happy and successful life (yes, iâ€™m looking at you, goop). in this session youâ€™ll learn how and why the diet and wellness industry is seducing you - as a smart and motivated woman - to place your hard earned dollars and precious headspace into their hands.Â in this session melissa burton, a former marketing manager and current registered dietitian nutritionist (and registered yoga teacher), will help you understand the depth, breath and power of diet culture and how to lessen its impact on your wallet, mind, heart and soul

text:
last week in ireland a man got away with rape just because of the type of thong the girl was wearing... a series of protests over sexual consent have been taking place, after a man was acquitted of raping a 17-year-old girl.

in the trail, the (female) defence lawyer told the jury: "you have to look at the way she was dressed. she was wearing a thong with a lace front." the man was found "not guilty"!! on tuesday, lawmaker ruth coppinger held up a lacy thong in ireland's parliament, to protest the goverment's inaction over the issue of sexual consent. 
#thisisnotconsent #sexualassault #sexualabuse #metoo #rapistcauserape #ruthcoppinger #istandwiththewomanofireland #stopvictimblaming #victimblaming #herbodyherchoice #herchoice #womansrights##nomeansno #timesup #feminism #cork #dublin #ireland

.
.
.

text:
why are we the most "connected" generation of all time, yet are in reality the most disconnected?

check out the link in bio for a short documentary called brain, heart, world. or view on the @fightthenewdrug profile.

one of the biggest problems is being connected physically, socially,Â or (or electronically), but disconnected in heart and soul.

porn is one of the biggest soul killers in our society? why? well one reason is its deceptiveness. it is sold as a connector, as an enhancer, and as "freedom" or liberty in sexuality.

in reality, it is bondage. not the "sexy" kind of bondage. the actual enslavement bondage. it is the disconnection of your brain, heart, and soul. it is the slow breakdown and separation of body, soul, and spirit.

think it doesnt affect you? i'd challenge you to learn some of the facts, and then think again.

this is a massive detriment to society. are you disgusted by men like harvey weinstein, who have sexually abused countless women? that mentality is driven and fueled by porn. it is allowed to to exist and grow. it is heralded. porn consumption ultimately drives human trafficking. 
as the statue of liberty is a symbol of freedom to the worn and weary who come to our country looking for a fresh beginning, i pray some of this scientific material will help bring freedom to the life of someone you know.

i don't share this to bring shame or condemnation on people. i share to bring light and awareness. this stuff isn't easy to talk about, just like it isn't easy for me to encourage someone who is really unhealthy and overweight to stop eating sugar. but i love that person enough to step in and help bring awareness to the damage being done, and show steps towards health and freedom. 
if you want to do the same, then share this message.

#freedomfriday #brainheartworld #nopornnovember #metoo  #humantraffickingÂ #makeachange
#truefreedom #statueofliberty

what perfect timing. in human design, the gate venus has been gate 44 since early october, per astrologer kim gould.

this is the gate of welcoming the royal bride. the bride is coming, she is pregnant with the heir to the throne. the castle and surrounding lands must be prepared for her.
how are you preparing for the pregnant bride who is approaching your gate right now? how are you making room for such aÂ powerful feminine presence to enter? how are you preparing yourself as her arrival changes everything forevermore?

what parts of you are you/your life are you are dying off and what are you cultivating and creating? what qualities will be taking your throne?

are you still free to love and relationship to your wounds?
are you ready to receive your equal within you and what does that look like?

robots can create, but there is always an underlying pattern, some sort of program.  we are moving beyond the program, beyond the scripted, the controlled, the absolute and into a new world of creation.Â  we are doing that by becoming conscious of what we value, what we love, what makes us happy and feel well.

how can we acknowledge what a fountain of wisdom we are and are becoming?

how i failed at a basic millenial bitch attempt:
.
so i dressed in leggings, oversized hoodie and black framed glasses. went to #starbucks. got my self some #organic #kombucha and #chailatte. it was very crowded but i found a spot. opened my #macbook. noticed i couldn't concentrate, and that the air was too hot and too thick and there were sweat beads on my forehead. looked atound: nobody seemed to struggle with breathing. great. panic attack in the making. left, spent 15 mins in the shower letting the water hide my tears (#sarcasm but cold relief is real). .
.
i never had such social anxiety in crowded places and transport before. it started after the sexual attack on me earlier this year. so some fucker decided to think with his penis, and here i am, getting lots of therapy and still freaking out in a coffee shop and in a train. funny, that.
.
.

text:
never alone

as often as these words have been expressed especially with the #metoo movement, i hope every single person reading this understands the power of simply reaching out.

i can't tell you how many times i needed to simply vent, needed to know someone â€“ anyone â€“ simply cared.

it breaks my heart to know we're so afraid of showing our weakness.

we're afraid of being judged.
we're afraid we'll look foolish.
but it's not worth it. our ego is not worth us staying in our lowest of lows.
it's not worth you having to deal with a broken heart on your own.

it's not worth you questioning your worth to your family, friends, to the world. 
it's not worth you feeling trapped with whatever deep dark secret you think will make you unlovable.

even if it's simply me â€“ a random stranger on instagram â€“ please send a message. do not wait until you're on your last string of sanity.

we all do a great job of sharing the 'pretty' mask to which everyone seems to enjoy. 
we tend to hold it all together. always smiling in pictures. looking flawless, on point, whatever.

that's. not. real.
it's not human.
we hurt. we hold on to pain. disappointment tear us apart.

if there's every anything i can ever do to listen, to help ease pain, or even just to reassure you you're not alone â€“ please give me that honor of serving you. please help me.
i need you to know you're loved, admired, worthy, & adored. 
you are never alone â™¥

text:
femme wave presents: sex hysteria afterimage [part 1/10]: an instagram exhibition by @prdct
.
. 
in the age of #metoo, sexual violence is front and center on everyoneâ€™s feeds. since the movementâ€™s virality began in late 2017, hundreds of people throughout the twitterverse have opened up to the internet with their experiences of sexual harassment and violence in the workplace. though #solidarity and strength through this sharing of experiences is overwhelmingly evident, one cannot help but notice willful ignorance in the midst of it all: a community left out of a conversation whose members should, in fact, be at the forefront of. .
.
#wherearethesexworkers? .
.
in conversations of #autonomy, #consent, and #violence against marginalized peoples, there is something to be said about the importance of the role of the sex worker. they have unique qualifications to speak on these topics, given their jobs and the astronomical levels of abuse and violence they face (they experience a higher rate of sexual harassment and assault than any other group of people), but are rarely invited to the conversation. more often than not, people working in the sex industry are pushed *out* of #metoo and other discussions on similar topics due to poor representation and stigmatism surrounding the identities of sex workers and how they make their moneyâ€¦ a consequence of hysteria created by the government and the media which has resulted in rampant #whorephobia, often topped with nuances of racism and sexism to boot. .
.
whorephobia: â€œthe hatred of, oppression of, violence towards, and discrimination against sex workers; and by extension derision or disgust towards activities or attire related to sex work.â€ .
.
at its best, it manifests as harmful stereotyping that lends itself to the spreading of damaging misinformation, resulting in the passing of unjust laws which only serve to push sex workers further underground. at its worst, whorephobia kills. 
_______

art [1/10] by @prdct
music by @deepsabrina
essay [1/10] by @buates.mckenzie

text:
jummah ke maukay par relevant picture se lutf andoz hoyen. 
yesterday i experienced an invigorating discussion on a ladies-in-law whatsapp group. it involved a forward regarding women of inappropriate outfits messing up aimaan of hazraat of this country and spreading lust.

my initial stance was that this is a one sided story and just because a girl walks in skinny jeans doesn't mean you pounce on her. our religion mentions pardaah for men before that of women. rape of young girls and boys happened and all we care about is what she wore? 
nobody teaches their son to rape women but hardly anyone teaches them to respect them. there is some old school romance associated with staring at a girl while she walks down the street. mix it up with screwed up upbringing and you get a harassment situation right here. whenever i talk about men discussing women and staring at them in a lewd manner i am told this is how it is. boys will be fudging boys, so guard your modesty.

i understand that. i love trends and fashion and i also use the #modestfashion hashtag, but i also dont cover my head in daily life save dangerous neighborhoods. obviously somebody will always, always disagree with your dressing.

moms, can we not teach boys not to stare? can we not teach them the #nomeansno concept? can we not create a non-judgmental situation. our own religion teaches not to judge and let ppl be, let them come to hidaayah. we shun and shame everyone but the perpetrator, the abuser.  we say, she deserved it. nobody deserves it. 
i comprehended from the discussion that safety measures are essential both for ourselves and our kids. evil exists. we need to guard against it. but are we looking for the cure in the wrong direction? we fix our dupatta but who fixes the weakened imaan of the pervert? i would love your thoughts on this.
.
.
.

nobody teaches their son to rape women but hardly anyone teaches them to respect them. there is some old school romance associated with staring at a girl while she walks down the street. mix it up with screwed up upbringing and you get a harassment situation right here. whenever i talk about men discussing women and staring at them in a lewd manner i am told this is how it is. boys will be fudging boys, so guard your modesty.

i understand that. i love trends and fashion and i also use the #modestfashion hashtag, but i also do not cover my head in daily life save dangerous neighborhoods. obviously somebody will always, always disagree with your dressing.

moms, can we not teach boys not to stare? can we not teach them the #nomeansno concept? can we not create a non-judgmental situation. our own religion teaches not to judge and let ppl be, let them come to hidaayah. we shun and shame everyone but the perpetrator, the abuser.  we say, she deserved it. nobody deserves it. 
i comprehended from the discussion that safety measures are essential both for ourselves and our kids. evil exists. we need to guard against it. but are we looking for the cure in the wrong direction? we fix our dupatta but who fixes the weakened imaan of the pervert? i would love your thoughts on this.
.
.
.

text:
yep thatâ€™s me!
finally a press article that is 100% factual and not sensationalising the difficult times that i went through. 
for me the whole point of my book was to live in my truth and get my readers to live in their truth. 
iâ€™m strong enough to bat some non factual press off but thatâ€™s not the point, not everyone is! this can cause further distress. letâ€™s not bat off lies, letâ€™s educate our generation and generations to come to not be afraid to speak up & be in their truth because all this does is cause anyone suffering further issues and will then stop people from talking about things then need to talk about. 
it took me years to find my courage to write my story. i never set out to be an author or share my story. i just know itâ€™s the right time and anne jirsch reminded me yesterday that if you feel it, then do it, itâ€™s intuitive and for me opening up my life story was.

i published my self help book to give hope and inspiration to anyone going through difficult times and thus far thatâ€™s what itâ€™s been doing, and across the globe. iâ€™ve had many messages from people thanking me, and saying itâ€™s given them hope and inspired them. some people have gone on to share their deepest darkest problems with not just me but loved ones. 
i would like to personally thank the henley herald for listening to me during our interview and producing this article.

also huge thanks to naz ahsun sarah parfitt julie green henley on thames susan meyers and all my friends for everything youâ€™ve supported me with! www.emmajanetaylor.life

text:
i am all for open dialogue and discussing tough topics.  iâ€™m so ignorant about much of whatâ€™s happening in the world, i appreciate having my eyes opened to new ideas and perspectives, even if this means facing my own privilege.  as a community of people both online and in real life, communication about important issues is essential to growth and this platform is a great way to mobilize.

while i love the ability for so many people to communicate on this platform, i am not a fan of people jumping on bandwagons to bring down others.  over the past few months iâ€™ve seen several instances in which women tear other women down.  all of this while posting #metoo and #feminist memes.  is there really a movement to support other women, or are most just waiting around for their opportunity to point the finger and participate in this destructive callout  culture that has become so popular. 
how do we really come together and support women in loving and productive ways?  we can have difficult conversations and be forced to look in the mirror, but once we start criticizing and looking for a community to join in, thatâ€™s when the growth stops and we start weakening one another.

text:
this is such an important article about the dangers of alcohol abuse and how challenging it is to treat. 
this quote was the most important part to me because it is so true. what other illness is left untreated these days?

we run around trying to avoid gluten and dairy and gmo but constantly laugh off the idea that alcohol is not safe, instead we lie to ourselves and believe the nonsense that it only hurts some people but it's safe for others. we would never smoke cigarettes in front of our children yet we drink around them and make jokes about it and exclude moms who don't drink. we would never tolerate it with any other drug, why is alcohol different?

it's time to end the stigma attached to alcoholics and substance abuse and change our behavior to be more accepting of someone's decision to say no thanks.

text:
awesome news!

jessie's song has already spoken hope into the lives of thousands of people...and i need your help to shout from the rooftops this weekend. please share this!

the kindle version of jessie's song will be free tomorrow and sunday! this means that thousands more people can receive a message of hope, belonging, and true identity through this story.

to download the free version, you must go to the amazon.com website in a web browser after 12am pacific time saturday morning. it won't show up on an app or kindle. also - you don't have to belong to kindle unlimited. it will be free for everyone! 
to make it super easy - here's a link: https://www.amazon.com/jessies-song-jeremy-williamson-ebook/dp/b075sktjjn/ref=sr_1_1?ie=utf8&qid=1542391644&sr=8-1&keywords=jessies+song

it sounds like the sale ends monday at midnight - so if you've never read jessie's song, grab a copy and encourage your friends to do the same!

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

cu devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text: life update! i feel so good. like the weight of the world has been lifted from my shoulders. i told that intern that was harassing me to stop because it made me feel uncomfortable. he said that he was sorry and wouldnâ€™t do it again. for the next few days, my boyfriend (who, yes, i know you all want to know who he is/what he looks like. that will happen soon - but love isn't the center of life, happiness is, so iâ€™m focusing on that) would come into my building with either lunch or a flower or just to say hi. he didnâ€™t like the idea of a fellow intern saying things like that to me, and i refused to let him address it himself, but we settled on little check-ins to make it known that i was taken and that my boyfriend is a very strong man lol. anyways, a few days later he decided to address me as a sexual object. he told a fellow intern (who sits right next to me - so yes he was right next to me) that he would gladly â€œpark his car in my garageâ€ while i bent down to grab the pen that i dropped. i looked right at him and told him that not only was that statement a terrible joke, but it qualified as sexual harassment and that i was going to report him to our boss and he could very well lose his position. he pleaded that he didnâ€™t mean to say it out loud, but he would have still been thinking it. so i did just that. today i told my boss what was going on. they had me file a report and then they called him in (while i was still there) and fired him! us girls should never have to deal with anything like this. i let it go on for too long, it made my life miserable while i was at my internship. but he will no longer torment me or any other woman. us women have a voice now. letâ€™s use it and scream at the top of our lungs for what we think is right. #metoo #mystory #sexualharassmentisneverokay

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
i wanted to give up so many times in my life. 
when life hits you hard, you feel like you're backed into a corner...suffocating...drowning in quicksand..waiting for someone to pull you out. waiting for life to get even just a little bit better.

you are faced with two options:
give up or put up one heck of a fight.

i have learned that the more you keep fighting through whatever it is you are dealing with, the stronger it is you become. i speak from experience, not just some cliche talking.

life is tough. right??? but if we give up now before life gets better again..we won't see the fruit of our works. our strength..our triumph! 
if you feel like giving up, hang in there. i know it may seem like a far fetched, unimaginable idea that life can get better, but it can. just hang in there. please...don't give up.

you are needed in this world. everything you encompass is extraordinary. it's unique. whether you believe the words i am typing or not. it's true.

i love you so much. just hang in there. fight. give it everything you got and a little more. i know you can do this.

don't give up on me..
never give up.

#youmatter
#iamthefaceof

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text: this is huge. i can't believe i'm actually saying it. the second project i wrote and directed has been selected for my local film festival! tally shorts is an awesome fest in tallahassee, florida that exclusively showcases awesome shorts made locally and internationally. i've been working and working and learning what it means to be a serious filmmaker for the past 7 years and this is an amazing opportunity to prove that all that work is paying off. i'm so privileged and excited to be able to share my story and give a voice to a problem that millions and millions of people face all the time. thank you to my awesome, talented, and good-looking cinematographer, brett allbritton. you bring so much to my life and i love the art we make together!! #film #filmmaker #florida #floridafilmmaker #womandirector #metoo #tallyshorts #tallyshortsfilmfestival #writtenanddirectedbyme

so i received this wonderful email today. before i say what exactly happened, i am not putting down or insulting  sex workers who choose their career, that being said i am not a sex worker. 
i posted in a local community forum for freelance work dog sitting, cleaning, and babysitting. 
i am about up to here with this bullshit. this uninvited sexual harrasment , simply because i am attractive i am perceived to "want it" , or "ask for these advances" it's enoughhhhhhh! i usually brush this off because it happens so often but this idiot put his full name so i'm putting it out there. women are afraid to put themselves out their and be independent because of shit like this. there are plenty of platforms available for that type of service , and hunny i am not the one. my post being clear, concise, and professional outlining my professional experiences with an appropriate head shot from the neck up ! like really asshole , come on please check yourself and make this world a safer space for women, and here's a fucking thought, #respect ,she doesn't ask for it , hunny it means she doesnt want it! women are not going to back down and brush this shit off any more so good luck ryan anderson . oh and that goes for couples too , sooo beyond over couples harrasing a lesbian to sleep with you two #thirsty asses, like again find like minded people for this!

text:
the theater at the 14th street y announces 2018-2019 season lgbtq+ series

the theater at the 14th street y continues tohonor the edgy, diverse, and rich history of innovative culture making in the east village for people of all ages with the 2018-2019 lgbtq+ series.the series kicked off on november 12, 2018 with #nastywomen, a night of female resistance comedy and runs through april 2019."for our season of war & peace, we knew that artists from the lgbtq community would have a strong reaction to the theme. coming out can often feel like war and creating a family can bring much needed peace. our lgbtq offerings this season have addressed the gamut, from vietnam veterans coming to terms with their sexuality to a tya show with a non-gender binary protagonist to a piece about a modern family facing discrimination from within. our theater is a safe place for provocative work that will inspire conversation, debate and hopefully action," said ronit muszkatblit, artistic director.different translation november 29 - december 16, 2018 written byÂ david stallings, directed by antonio miniÃ±o when claire's concerns over the welfare of her two-year old cousin are dangerously validated, she begins to question the family's principals and ability to parent. a crucial new play, exploring same-sex parenting and cis family values in today's america. after the december 7 performance, guests will be invited to an lgbtq mixer with free drinks and appetizers with the cast and crew.Â a night of female resistance comedy
comedyistheresistance.com
january 28, april 15, may 20, 2019
curated by laura beatrix newmark
following the women's march and in light of the #metoo, time's up, #neveragain movements, we provide a forum for female comedians that empowers all through laughter, camaraderie and tangible activism tools. nasty women's second season includes a show in april celebrating her, they and us, from comedians of transgender experience. #commentsplease #explorepageğŸ˜ #lgbtqtravelers #pleasecomments #200likes #lgbtqiapd #commentsğŸ˜» #followers #commentsğŸµğŸ’— #10likes #jualfollowers #lgbtqğŸŒˆ #autocomments #100likes #20likes #lgbtqcommunity #explorepageâ¤ï¸ #ilovemyfollowers #explorepageâœ¨

comedyistheresistance.com
january 28, april 15, may 20, 2019
curated by laura beatrix newmark
following the women's march and in light of the  time's up,  movements, we provide a forum for female comedians that empowers all through laughter, camaraderie and tangible activism tools. nasty women's second season includes a show in april celebrating her, they and us, from comedians of transgender experience.

text:
feeling really good to announce this upcoming workshop i am facilitating at stretch vancouver on december 16, from 7-9pm.  tickets at eventbrite, link in my bio. 
this #metoo beathwork event is the first of its kind, and has been carefully made for the healing of anyone who has been subjected to sexual abuse of any kind. 
in this two hour workshop, we will connect with other people who have also experienced sexual abuse, harassment, rape, or assault, and give each other a chance to be heard and release anything that's ready to come out.
we will also be doing one hour of clarity breathwork, which is a continuous breathing technique that floods the body with oxygen and helps to reset the nervous system. it also can allow traumas to be released from the body, and provide great clarity on how we truly feel inside. that gives way to a deeper connection with self, and the body which is often dissociated after abuse.

this is a place to heal, and let go, without fear of judgement. we will create a supportive container together, in the hopes that each of us can leave feeling a bit lighter, and a bit more connected to both the self and the greater community because this is an issue that has impacted so many of us.

come to try it out, come to connect, come to heal.

i look forward to seeing you there, this is an issue that is near and dear to my heart. it is my wish to help create a safe space beyond the hashtags, where we can come together in community to heal and move forward.

please ask any questions you may have, see you then. -asta

text:
may we heal from this #fire. may we find our path to global #healing. may our missing aunties, neighbors, and friends be found #alive. if not, may we as their grieving survivors claim our #voice and #money from those entities who created the disaster if it wasnâ€™t of natural, earthly origins. 
#reparations means repairing the damage that can be fixed and using community #knowledge to prevent future losses of the same #kind. below are some ideas about how to calculate for financial reparations. this is a work in progress. under conditions of intense vulnerability, i practice â€œquick releaseâ€ aka â€œ#rapidprototyping. 
first, there is no one method or formula for determining reparations.

so much of the violence we experience is personalized. the violence we experience is always shared by other people and communities, yet how it affects us is embodied and related to who we are in this earth #walk. that's why this method was designed for people like you and #metoo.

second, calculating reparations is always an #economic and #spiritual practice.

above all, the spiritual dimension of this method is central, and #survivors must lead each #initiative. the point is to foster healing, not pay for therapy and legal costs, and give people the support we require to create solutions for ourselves and our #beloved communities. so, what does healing mean for you as a survivor of the violence you seek to stop? given your daily life and needs at this time, what do you need to put in place to learn and apply the method?

from a purely economic perspective, what aspects of healing can financial reparations facilitate? this question is the most direct, but it isn't as simple as it sounds. for example, you might desire therapy and know that therapists cost a rate of, say $60-250 an hour in your town. what if no therapist in your local beloved community speaks your mother language of #quechua or #spanish or #tagalog and that's the language in which you sense the world? what is the honest price tag for your therapy sessions if you have to travel three hours to see a therapist who shares your cultural, linguistic, ancestral #perspective?

text:

text:
for the last two years, i've been working on a project to decolonize social enterprise and help folks work together to regenerate our global ecosystem and practice beloved community. you can read more about that in other posts to this blog or do a search for #decolonialbiznessworld on this platform or elsewhere if you're curious.

the focus of this post is the lessons i've learned from linkedin.

i didn't plan to create a method of business education aimed at reparations and decolonization. it just happened. decolonial bizness world came to me post-hack.

you see, for the last four years i've been the target of hackers, some known and others not. you can find posts on being hacked in the archive of writings you see here, on linkedin, if you search my writing. i won't include links directly because, well, that's not the focus. this tidbit is for context.

two years ago, after many hacks of small and large impact, i lost everything in what i've come to call a "full stack hack." in the world of engineering, a full stack developer is someone who handles all aspects of digital systems, from databases to servers and clients to apps. i use the term full stack hack to speak to my life after i lost access to:

1ï¸âƒ£the digital archives that stored my papers such as half a completed book manuscript, syllabi, and notes from more than a decade;
2ï¸âƒ£my personal and academic email accounts; and
3ï¸âƒ£my phone.
no joke. my phone got #smoky and was #toast in mere minutes. the #smoke effect was a sight to behold. it started in the bottom right corner and kept going and growing until #goodbye smartphone.

all this happened within a week or so. i don't recall the details or exact timeline; i was terrified and the consequences were swift and long-lasting. posts from that time also appear in this archive, as this platform was one of the few i was able to access during that full stack hack of my life/work.

since that time, i've used this blog to share drafts and more polished work. i've made edits and even complete deletions to what you can view -- and #metoo. the digital imprint remains in the cloud.

the focus of this post is the lessons i have learned from linkedin.

i didn't plan to create a method of business education aimed at reparations and decolonization. it just happened. decolonial bizness world came to me post-hack.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
in "broke," #lecrae testifies to how poverty can make people #wealthy. isn't that a #beautiful teaching? and how #sweet to see a leader who makes sense!

we need our #prophets of truth to displace the lie of profit.

this idea is central to the teachings of #decolonialbiznessworld. in decolonial bizness world, there's the #soil of natural #abundance at the base of the #treeoflife, which starts at the heart with #selflove and includes #belovedcommunity and true love for #mothernature, who's now on strike.

you see, when i'm not pushed into the position of having to call out tech companies like #google, #facebook, and #linkedin for protecting #predators, i'm drawing upon community knowledge to help people #decolonize business #leadership so that we can transform a world system that creates financial poverty and profits from it.

as if that is the only form of violence at play in the world today. #4645boricuas.

in the case of #facebook, for example, a sexual predator or collection of them used my full legal name, darshan elena campos, to sell porn and sex via facebook for at least two months. i'll spare you all the details but this truth: facebook refused to remove the page. one day, it just disappeared. #poof.

i have been locked out of posting images and videos to instagram since 4 july 2018 when i organized a free event, which asked what freedom means to #nativepeoples, slaves, colonial subjects, and babies locked in a cage. i can't delete what's pending, and i can't log out either.

i am trapped.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
trigger warning, a panic attack #share on being the target of hackers, at least one of whom is a known sexual predator and a google engineer.

today i need to go to the apple store. i need to buy the right cable for the laptop i have so that it can plug into the community energy grid at the #farm where i spend a lot of time. the farm runs on living #energy, not fossil energy like oil and gas, so i need a new set of cords.

i'm going there, to the farm, since i'm less #safe in my home community than on the road or migratory. i'm also going to the farm because i'm #boricua (google #4645boricuas) and invested in climate #solutions. there, i'm designing starter kits for #freeglobaldistribution of the farm's community energy grid. i'm not an engineer or a tech writer, but i'm #smart, handy, and pretty #resilient in the face of personal and political disaster.

although resilient, i'm panicky at the moment because it isn't just a new cable. my entire digital system of devices is being pesky, and i need to look at that too. and that's the point of this post: #digital (in)#security for colored girls who want to live when we're a moving target.

truth: my iphone only #rings when it wants to. the texts never #beep. even people who use iphones don't understand my smartphone. my phone's challenges stumped a #13 year old who has an apple phone, which says a lot.

so you see, i'm panicky because it isn't just a trip to the store in #preparation for farm life below the mason-dixon line. it is a trip down trauma lane, which makes no sense and goes round and round, before i leave the house in st. louis where i've been for the last week. for the last two months i've been here, in st. louis, and this is the fourth home i've stayed in.

you confused yet? #metoo. let's do some trauma mapping together. i'll just tell the tale as it wants to be told.

donâ€™t waste your time stressing over the one thing that you couldnâ€™t get to; stress over missing the big things that matter - like time with family and friends. tomorrow is not given.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin

bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with ficial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
a few days ago someone close to me was walking home alone  around 8 pm when a piece of shit of a man grabbed her and was able to immobilize her while her screems got the attention of a neighbors dog and the neighbor was able to save her from what it would have been a violent rape right here in mairena, in what is one of the lowest crime areas in all of seville. 
the perpetuator, 16-20 year old, tall, dark hair, totally normal looking guy ran away and was not found.
the idea of this happening to anyone close to me horrifies me and fills me with tears, the idea that this happens every minute to a girl around the world makes me sick.

my inner circle is curated with pretty amazing people, both man and women uncapable of such thing, so i never ask myself questions like:
what was in his fucking mind? what gives him right?
what can we do to stop this from happening? what makes a man do something like this?  who is rasing this kind of monsters? what can i do???? why don't we talk about this kind of thing when it happens? why does it bring shame to the victim? so on and so on... and i come back to around a year ago to a wedding, when an a acquaintance , slid his fingers on back, saying total  inappropriate sexual comments...etc... i left the party and removed myself from the enviroment instead of confronting the man helping normalize this kind of shit. yeah, and i could go on with stories like that from the past some what similar to the last and see a clear pattern: some ashole says something stupid, i get away, don't talk about it and even make excuses (he just doesn't have commun sense. he had just too much to drink. he is annoying but he doesn't mean it like that, i propably said something to encourrage him) are we active part of the problem?
we should be able to walk home alone, or go to a party, or dress how ever the fuck we want with out being hassared or even rape. but reality indicates other wise. 
we need to protect ourselves, talk about when it happens and confront when we are being harrased. is not ok to not feel safe. 
my heart goes out to all of you girls who had been in similar situation. i'm sorry the world is so fucked up. #metoo
