text: my first clay sculpture in college, and first time with polymer clay. the concept was really important to me, so i went all out with meticulous planning, anatomical research, measuring and countless hours. it became truly a form of art therapy. however once i fired it i fell into a bit of a slump internally, as i had been focusing so much energy on this piece. i realize now that it is a testament to resilience and self compassion in ways i never intended. it is finally sculpted and fired, however still some perfectionist fine tuning... artist statement to come once the piece is completely finished in mid december... #polymerclay #nudesculpture #compassion #universalcompassion #metoo #anatomystudy

text: â€¢ kingsley amis was brilliant at portraying otherwise ordinary characters in an incisively funny way, and this novel was no exception. there's jenny, the 'chaste' & very pretty young teacher, away from home for the first time and having to fend off the lascivious advances of her boyfriend patrick, and her creepy landlord dick thompson. the novel recounts jenny's experience entering the world of work in 1960 britain and the dynamics of dealing with a boyfriend with only one aim in mind. up to a point patrick was a sort of likeable cad, i mean lad, and then his conduct at a drunken party put him squarely in the criminal category and would at the very least have made him a candidate for the #metoo movement if it had existed in 1960, which it did not, clearly. so there are interesting issues of consent here, in a book very much of its era, but read against a 2018 backdrop. i would like to think that even in 1960 this character's conduct was received with censure, but i'm not sure it was. sigh ... â€¢

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
the end not proven campaign was launched by myself and @rapecrisisscotland this week. with the huge help of @bbcnews @stv.news and the fabulous @fidjit and @pieute â¤ï¸ .
the not proven verdict is used disproportionately in rape cases. 
in 2016/17, only 39% of rape and attempted rape cases resulted in convictions, the lowest rate for any type of crime. nearly 30% of acquittals were not proven, compared with 17% for all crimes and offences.

the not proven verdict has the exact same impact as a not guilty verdict, and can be just as distressing for the complainer as a not guilty verdict.

i am calling on the scottish government to give survivors a chance. there is no convincing argument to retain the outdated verdict, itâ€™s time to scrap not proven for good.

image credit: @fidjit 
please share this information and spread the word about this important campaign.

#fightingforjustice

text:
i was recently put in this situation. no choice. i wish i was able to say the same as what is said in the picture, but i froze up, just like the first time. 
you might be like... but why are you even telling me this? because... we are shaped by many things. trauma is a big contributor to the way we are today, personality wise or even mental illnesses that took form. we need to learn to be more tolerant and patient with one another. you never know what people are going through. talk to your loved ones. be there for them. love them. show them that you love them for who they've become. we need to know that. 
i am not someone that share personal things, but i'm honored to have this anonymous platform, something which many in the same situation don't have. so i need to use it to just get people talking, thinking in critical ways as to how we can break the stigma. let me know if you want to work on something or just share a story. â£#mentalillness #mentalillnessmemes #mentalhealth #proud #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealthmatters #bipolarmemes #bipolar #bipolardisorder #bipolarsurvivor #bipolarawareness #bipolarquotes #suicidesurvivor #bipolar1 #bipolar2 #manic #depressed #hypomanic #yourenotalone #endthestigma #inthistogether #mentalhealth #loveyourself #youaregoodenough #sexualassault #metoo #believesurvivors #whyididntreport #timesup
name: Reality of Bipolar Disorder

text:
.
i know i'm not alone
when i feel confronted
when i ponder...
what does it mean
to be a woman in 2018?

today i sat with local women
under a big ass tree
many of whom
i've never met before
(where have i been?)
.
determined not to cry
(not yet! too soon!)
before a word was uttered
before anyone shared
their story...
.
i sat under that tree
with my kids
and felt our collective strength
our collective energy
our power.

and boy, we are strong
you wouldn't wanna
fuck with us
not any of us.

yet we will hear you
we will listen
there is no anger
just smiles
understanding
and nods.

i am feeling incredibly honoured to be a part of jsp's next event coming up in february 2019 and i can't wait to share more with you here soon xx

text:
part 1:
i was sexually assaulted when i was 16. i was with a (female) friend at that day, who had also invited another (male, 20-something at the time) friend of hers, i didn't know him before, but we got along great. i live about two to three hours from my friend when i take the bus, however, the guys parents don't live far from me, so he offered to drive me home in order to visit them afterwards. i gladly agreed, since that would take less than an hour, also i enjoyed talking to him. in the car, he asked me if i wanted to hang out a little more, since it wasn't even afternoon, i agreed. 
however, while we were driving it started to get uncomfortable. earlier the day, i already stated that i was gay (i don't remember why exactly we talked about it, but the point is, he knew) and he started to go on and on about how that was "such a pity", i'm "too pretty to be a lesbian" and how i was totally his type. i pretty much just chuckled nervously at everything he said, confirming i was gay and not at all interested over and over again, already not really wanting to hang out anymore, but also too shy to tell him that. he stopped the car at some field, a few minutes drive away from the next village (or any civilization at all, really) and we sat down in the backseat to talk. i thought that we just could get over the conversation about me being gay and just talk about something else, but nothing really felt right or comfortable anymore and i already couldn't wait for an excuse to get home. then, he kissed me. i was in shock and didn't react at all. he proceeded to touch my body, especially my boobs and butt, also sliding his hands between my legs, telling me how sexy i was. i didn't manage to do anything besides staring at him (and i still hate myself for that), only finally reacting as he put my hand on his crotch, i pulled it away. however, the next twenty minutes or so, he still continued to touch me, putting his hands under my shirt, kissing me, "complimenting" me and i still was too much in shock to really react. 
#metoo #sexualassault #depression #advice

society is arranged in such a wayÂ  as "what is between your legs is determined more than just your gender". i've noticed that there are a lot of yoni, vagina and pussy campaigns popping up the last year. this probably also has to do with the #metoo movement. the third feminist wave seems to be a fact nowadays. i'm calling myself a (prosexual) feminist as well but i've noticed that this word is been used so often that it sometimes loses it's impact/strength. sometimes i'm asking myself why it's called feminism? does this mean that there are two types of women? and why ain't there two types of man? the men is socially presented as powerful and dominant. that brings me to the answer that i'm always giving when people ask me about how i look at feminism and how i see myself as a feminist. to me man and women are different. we do have different genitals which have their own characteristics. we do have different ways of experiencing. but don't we have that all? as we all have our own individual feelings, beliefs and experiences. to me being a feminist is to strive for the same chances. to me feminism is about self-recognition, appreciation and development. to me feminism is about being the women who i want to be. without forced into the shackles of the social women image. what about you?

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the companyâ€™s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
this evening @yogarootspetoskey â¤ï¸âœ¨ a safe, sacred space for survivors to gather in grace. this healing circle will explore self-care techniques to heal spiritual and emotional pain. learn how to use affirmations, mindfulness and breath work to cultivate acceptance and inner peace. our time together will include gentle yoga and a sound healing session. 
this is our second meeting, new-comers are welcome. at the first meeting we discussed our coping mechanisms. two suggestions made by group members, one a burn journal, and the second a love letter to one's self have become themes for our next meeting. inspired by these suggestions we will start with a fire, where you may burn any journaled pages you want to let go of, anything you don't want others to read. then we will circle up inside and read the love letters (optional), and continue our discussion on self-care and coping mechanisms. we will conclude our gathering with gentle/restorative yoga and end with sound healing. 
this event is donation based, proceeds will benefit the women's resource center. door will be locked at the start of event, please arrive early. studio entrance is through the back door off the alley.

tiffany lenau, founder of yoga roots, it a sexual assault survivor of 20+ years. after healing her own wounds she is ready to share her coping skills with others and is honored to hold space for others on their path to healing. 
#newday
#metoo
#timesup

this event is donation based, proceeds will benefit the women's resource center. door will be locked at the start of event, please arrive early. studio entrance is through the back door off the alley.

tiffany lenau, founder of yoga roots, it a sexual assault survivor of 20+ years. after healing her own wounds she is ready to share her coping skills with others and is honored to hold space for others on their path to healing.

text:
god is alpha & omega, but he is also medio! 
god can, at anytime, clear up the mess. one may ask, but when i was in the middle of that mess where was god? in the middle god was silent. in the middle i was alone. 
in the middle, in the furnace of affliction, we are refined. 
the middle is where we learn how to utterly rely on him.  the middle is where made to examine ourselves & our motives. the middle is where shedding takes place. a shedding that refines us and draws us closer to him.

so wait for his timing and learn all he wants you to learn in your middle moments.

romans 8:28 assures us that "god causes all things to work together for good to those who love him, to those who are called according to his purpose." but the next verse tells us how god works all things for good in our lives: "for those whom he foreknew, he also predestined to become conformed to the image of his son...." there it is. god wants us to become more like his son through our struggles. so be teachable. be open to what he wants you to learn. and be moldable. you - and your heart - might be the one reason god has not yet fixed the situation.

text:
"heyy, you know, she wore 'salwar kameez' in our annual day. so old fashioned she is."
we usually judge people this way, right? we usually measure the level of their fashion on the basis of clothes they wear. we think that fashion is always about short-tops and hot-pants but heyy, please don't think that way. fashion isn't always about clothes but sometimes it's about how comfortable we are in them. yes it is! if you're feeling comfortable in short-tops, you're fashionable. if you're comfortable in hot-pants, you are fashionable. if you're comfortable in salwar-kameez, you're fashionable. if you're comfortable in hijaab, you're fashionable. let them judge. choose your comfort, choose your fashion.
.
.
Â©anjali @uncaged_emotions_ 
__________________________

pic credits: nezha

jnicsr foundation is pleased to announce the official launch of jnicsr times magazine vol.3 issue. 11. the much awaited magazine, was developed in cooperation with team jnicsr. we offer rich and relevant content that reflects the corporate social responsibility, personality and vivacity. jnicsr times will be on the web at www.jnicsrtimes.com. the magazine was unveiled in new delhi this morning, with full team and family of jnicsr foundation.

this time jnicsr times is  featuring a cover story on â€œa csr can help reduce the great gender divide: #me too movement is a great step in the history of women empowerment â€ and introducing jnicsr following articles:

1.  promotion of education, special education and vocational skills.

the visual and editorial quality of jnicsr times is top-notch and its pages are inspired by the values and interests of corporate social responsibility. the magazineâ€™s style is elegant and sparkling, simple and contemporary, and creates an inviting world that has something for underprivileged and poor in every area of their lives. readers will find special sections that include cover story, article and current updates of csr. â€œjnicsr foundation is very proud to be associated with jnicsr times, one of the most admired and respected csr magazine.

after hours and days of work, we can finally unveil our vol.3 issue. 11! what a delight! working on the vol.3 issue. 11 was a highly enriching experience for us and we want to thank the fabulous team at jnicsr times for their collaboration and support in this magnificent adventure.

text:
"when we say the future belongs to young people, who are these young people? the ones who are sneaked out of their countries for sex trade? the ones who are denied basic education? the ones who languish in poverty and hopelessness? who are these young people we keep talking about?" writes vigilance atieno on her latest blog post.

just like you, vigilance odoyo believes in the potential and power of youth, but she dares to ask the questions that have been lingering on our minds for a while now. 
according to asec, the countries with the highest rates of modern slavery in sub-saharan africa are central african republic, democratic republic of the congo, somalia, south sudan, sudan and mauritania. â€œgovernments wake up, protect and serve your citizens!â€ pleads @vigilance_odoyo .

text: i can hardly leave my house without getting catcalled. iâ€™m serious. sometimes on days when i donâ€™t have anywhere to be, i stay home just to avoid conflict. iâ€™ve had people tell me i should be flattered by the attention. that iâ€™m lucky to be *this* beautiful. but itâ€™s not complimentary. being harassed daily is not a badge of honor. and i know the actual reason has little to do with my appearance: itâ€™s because the objectification of women of color has been normalized by the white patriarchy. so normalized, in fact, that when they do find us appealing (*gasp*), they have to justify it by categorically segregating us, then marginalize us further by using descriptors and qualifiers that are rooted in racism. think about the use of the word â€œexoticâ€ to describe a womanâ€™s appearance. by definition, that word means foreign. alien. strange. unusual. think about the phrase â€œpretty for a ______ girl.â€ whenâ€™s the last time you can remember that blank being filled in by the word â€œwhiteâ€? we are taught that non-white beauty is not normal. and this is one of the reasons why wocs are abused and assaulted as at such higher rates than white women. my freshman year of college, i met a white man who wanted to sleep with a woman of every race by the end of the academic year. he had an actual list in his wallet. and he told me- without shame or hesitation- that he wanted to hook up with me so he could check off two races at once. then he groped me without my consent. then he called me a prude when i wouldnâ€™t â€œgo furtherâ€ than that. he told me that no one would want to be with me because i was so uptight, and that my beauty was going to waste since i wasnâ€™t sexually engaging with anyone. this is just one of i-donâ€™t-even-know-how-many experiences iâ€™ve had in my life. and i know that i am just one of countless woc who have experienced things like this. stop othering non-white beauty. itâ€™s not a compliment. itâ€™s not flattering. itâ€™s gross. and itâ€™s dangerous. #notyourbaby #metoo #endrapeculture #survivor #believesurvivors #woc #intersectionalfeminism

text:
#metoo
i will share about something i hear or get contacted a lot about and something i have experienced.it is subject of #sexualabuse and it's relation to outfit. i don't want to write a lot but what i want all the girls out there understand is that it is never your fault when you are harrassed or what is worse raped. no matter what you dress like there is a certain type of men which is a majority type ( in my humble opinion) who will abuse you. just learn to respond. it is something we are never taught and when we speak up we get the blame. #blamingvictim is very common practice in all countries around the world. never be afraid to talk about it and never feel you are to blame. you are innocent it is them who did this to you. don't feel you are filthy and undeserving of love. you are beautiful, wonderful creature who had to experience terrible things but dont let this stop you from living life to its fullest. dont change and hide yourself. do not ruin your life and again never take the blame. lastly, always always speak up, fight back. you are the hero who will save you. no one else will. 
#girlpower

text:
holiday tip 2..
keep a close eye on your kids when the holiday "spirits" are flowing. many predators look for ways to get their victims to like them or think they are cool so they can gain their trust and ultimately abuse them. breaking the rules by allowing a kid to drink or even giving them alcohol to dull their senses so they aren't fully aware of what is being done to them are ways a predator can abuse a victim in a family setting and no one will be any the wiser. the predator will then use the kid's willingness to break the rules by drinking to blame, shame and/or threaten them into silence. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

text:
i attended the tata literature fest today and i'm as happy as one can be. words make me feel loved and hugged and enough all at the same time. 
i heard strong women like kalki koechlin (taking a moment to be a fan girl because i got her autograph!), harnidh kaur and various others speak about the #metoo movement. the session with karan thapar and sagarika ghose was amazing and the one where shobhaa de conversed with upamaniyu chatterjee only made the day better. 
while i was sitting there on the pink seat as a part of the audience, i almost imagined how wonderful would it be to finally become a great author.
someday i hope i step into the tata theatre, walk right inside, glance at the pink seats and keep walking till i reach the stage where i take the mic and greet the people there as an author.
i know it's a big dream. a very big one.
but i have a tiny and silly theory in life.
if we settle for less and don't dream big, we might not lose anything but we also stop the magic that could be meant for us.
when we do dream big, we have a lot to lose because dreaming is a hard work, my friend. however, this way we are at least aiming for the moon. and a wise man has already told us what happens when we aim for the moon. yes, we land between the stars.
so, this is me, dreaming big and being crazy enough to actually think they will come true.
someday i'll come for the tata literature festival as an author. call me crazy, but i actually do think this will happen.
the universe and i have a strong connection. i ask for something and it opens up ways for me.
let me leave you with a secret.
don't ever ask the universe for less than you want because it grants only what we ask.
be courageous and ask it to make all your 'oh my god, this is insane' dreams true, and it will.
it always will.
that's my promise :)
.
.
.
.
.
.
